docs.lead_paragraph: Early next month, Oregon will become the only place in the world where doctors may legally help patients end their lives. With that comes a leap into the unknown: the hows, whens and whys of state-sanctioned suicide. Edged into law by a bare majority of Oregon voters on Nov. 8, the decriminalization of assisted suicide is a triumph for groups that have been trying for years to wrest life-and-death decisions away from the state and the medical profession.

headline.main: Suicide Law Placing Oregon On Several Uncharted Paths
